docs.abstract: The consulting firm is the latest to invest heavily in artificial intelligence, even as big businesses grapple with the potential fallout from the technology.
docs.snippet: The consulting firm is the latest to invest heavily in artificial intelligence, even as big businesses grapple with the potential fallout from the technology.
docs.lead_paragraph: As the corporate world reckons with the impact that artificial intelligence may have on, well, everything, the consulting firm Accenture announced on Tuesday that it will invest $3 billion in the technology over the next three years.

headline.main: Accenture Makes a $3 Billion Bet on A.I.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: A quantum computer came up with better answers to a physics problem than a conventional supercomputer.
docs.snippet: A quantum computer came up with better answers to a physics problem than a conventional supercomputer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Quantum computers today are small in computational scope — the chip inside your smartphone contains billions of transistors while the most powerful quantum computer contains a few hundred of the quantum equivalent of a transistor. They are also unreliable. If you run the same calculation over and over, they will most likely churn out different answers each time.

headline.main: Quantum Computing Advance Begins New Era, IBM Says
headline.print_headline: Quantum Computing Could Begin a New Era
